# Free Food-Costing Sheets Strategy

## Purpose

This note captures research on the free spreadsheet/template landscape for restaurant food costing and inventory management. It is intended as reusable context for future agents working on strategy, product planning, SEO, lead magnets, or template production for `Foodcosting.app`.

## Executive Summary

Free Excel and Google Sheets templates are a validated acquisition channel in restaurant software.

The most relevant competitors are not generic template libraries. They are restaurant SaaS companies using spreadsheets as top-of-funnel assets, then moving users toward software once spreadsheet limits become painful.

The strongest opportunity for `Foodcosting.app` is not to publish many thin templates. It is to publish a focused family of genuinely useful Google Sheets products that:

- solve common restaurant costing workflows
- feel modern and easy to use
- are designed for Google Sheets first, with Excel compatibility second
- use real food-costing logic, not generic spreadsheet layouts
- naturally transition users into the app for automation, collaboration, and multi-location control

## Core Market Takeaways

- Free sheet/template strategy is common in restaurant and hospitality SaaS.
- Inventory, food cost %, recipe costing, COGS, and par sheets are the most common spreadsheet categories.
- Most providers pair the template with educational content and a soft or direct upsell into software.
- The market is active, but many assets are still dated, spreadsheet-heavy, or poorly differentiated.
- There is room to win with better UX, stronger Google Sheets-native design, and a clearer spreadsheet-to-app journey.

## Most Relevant Competitors

### Apicbase

Positioning:
Free food cost spreadsheet for Excel and Google Sheets, tied directly to recipe costing, menu pricing, COGS control, and theoretical margin tracking.

What stands out:

- strong spreadsheet-to-software bridge
- recipe and menu pricing focus
- cost updates propagate when ingredient prices change
- includes utility and preparation costs
- upsell clearly framed around variance control, inventory, purchasing, and multi-unit operations

Strategic read:
Best model for how to use a free sheet as the first rung of a product ladder.

Source:
https://get.apicbase.com/food-cost-spreadsheet/

### Supy

Positioning:
Free restaurant inventory template in Excel, Google Sheets, and PDF, packaged like lightweight software.

What stands out:

- modern packaging
- clear multi-tab architecture
- strong onboarding and how-to guidance
- settings, item master, stock count, and summary report structure
- explicit content about essential spreadsheet columns and the operational limits of spreadsheets

Known 2026 structure:

- How To Use
- Settings
- Item Master
- Kitchen Stock Count
- Bar Stock Count
- Summary Report

Strategic read:
Best reference for how to make a spreadsheet feel like a system rather than a blank template.

Sources:
https://supy.io/blog/free-restaurant-inventory-management-template
https://supy.io/blog/learn-restaurant-inventory-spreadsheet-guide

### RestaurantOwner

Positioning:
Deep menu and recipe costing workbook for serious operators.

What stands out:

- inventory master converts purchase unit cost to recipe unit cost
- support for ingredients, menu items, and sub-recipes
- dropdown-based entry
- automatic recalculation when ingredient prices change
- printable recipe cards without cost info
- real workbook depth rather than a simple one-tab sheet

Strategic read:
Best reference for spreadsheet logic and real-world costing complexity.

Source:
https://www.restaurantowner.com/public/DOWNLOAD-Menu-Recipe-Cost-Spreadsheet-Template-2.cfm

### TouchBistro

Positioning:
Educational content plus downloadable templates for inventory and par management.

What stands out:

- strong content-wrapper approach
- beginner-friendly explanations
- adjacent operational templates like inventory and par sheets
- useful examples of how to make a template page rank and teach

Strategic read:
Best reference for pairing downloadable sheets with SEO and educational content.

Sources:
https://www.touchbistro.com/blog/restaurant-inventory-template/
https://www.touchbistro.com/blog/restaurant-par-sheet-template/

### 7shifts

Positioning:
Simple food cost percentage template used as top-of-funnel acquisition.

What stands out:

- low cognitive load
- narrow and clear use case
- very direct CTA into the product
- strong awareness-stage utility

Strategic read:
Best reference for lightweight, easy-to-adopt sheet offers.

Source:
https://www.7shifts.com/resources/templates/restaurant-food-cost-template/

### Backbar

Positioning:
Template cluster strategy focused on inventory, COGS, bar operations, and adjacent calculators.

What stands out:

- not just one template, but a family of related resources
- inventory, COGS, par worksheet, liquor cost, pour cost, and related tools
- good example of turning templates into a resource hub

Strategic read:
Best reference for cluster strategy and resource-library thinking.

Sources:
https://www.getbackbar.com/bar-inventory-spreadsheet-excel-template
https://www.getbackbar.com/cost-goods-sold-calculator-template-restaurant-bar

### Lineup.ai

Positioning:
Simple, approachable restaurant inventory spreadsheet template.

What stands out:

- beginner-friendly
- easy to understand
- lower complexity than Supy or RestaurantOwner
- good example of accessible packaging for smaller operators

Strategic read:
Best reference for a low-friction entry-level template.

Source:
https://www.lineup.ai/free-restaurant-templates/inventory-sheet/

## Competitor Pattern Summary

### Pattern 1: Article + Template

Most strong providers wrap the sheet in an explanatory landing page rather than offering only a raw file.

Implication:
Each `Foodcosting.app` sheet should have its own SEO-friendly landing page with guidance, examples, and CTAs.

### Pattern 2: Spreadsheet First, Software Second

Better providers explicitly frame the sheet as a useful first step, while making it clear that software becomes valuable when complexity increases.

Implication:
The upsell should happen at natural pain points, not as a hard sell.

### Pattern 3: System Sheets Beat Blank Sheets

The strongest spreadsheet products feel structured. They often include a settings area, master data, calculation sheets, and summary/report tabs.

Implication:
Templates should feel like products, not freebies.

### Pattern 4: Clusters Beat One-Off Downloads

Providers with several related templates and calculators create stronger brand association and more internal linking opportunities.

Implication:
Think in terms of a Google Sheets product line, not isolated downloads.

### Pattern 5: Inventory and Food Cost Are the Main Entry Points

The most common and visible sheet categories are:

- inventory
- food cost percentage
- recipe and menu costing
- COGS
- par levels

Implication:
Start with familiar demand before moving into more specialized tools.

## Strategic Gap for Foodcosting.app

Very few competitors combine all of the following at once:

- modern UX
- Google Sheets-native design
- serious food-costing logic
- a cohesive family of related templates
- a clear transition into a dedicated food-costing app

This is likely the best opening for `Foodcosting.app`.

Recommended positioning:

`Free Google Sheets that restaurant teams actually want to use. Built for real food costing, not generic spreadsheet clutter. When you outgrow the sheet, Foodcosting.app is the next step.`

## Recommended Product Structure

Use a two-track strategy.

### Track 1: Quick Sheets

Purpose:
Simple, high-intent, easy-to-adopt resources for search and lead capture.

Suggested sheets:

- Food Cost Percentage Sheet
- Prime Cost Sheet
- Par Level Sheet
- Menu Price Calculator Sheet

Primary competitor references:

- 7shifts
- TouchBistro
- Lineup.ai

### Track 2: System Sheets

Purpose:
Richer, multi-tab spreadsheets that act like lightweight operating systems.

Suggested sheets:

- Recipe and Menu Costing Workbook
- Inventory and COGS Workbook
- Yield and Portion Cost Workbook

Primary competitor references:

- Apicbase
- Supy
- RestaurantOwner

## Initial Build Priorities

Recommended order:

1. Recipe and Menu Costing Workbook
2. Inventory and COGS Workbook
3. Food Cost Percentage Quick Sheet
4. Par Level and Order Guide Sheet
5. Yield and Edible Portion Sheet

Why this order:

- strong alignment with the core `Foodcosting.app` product
- highest market familiarity
- best bridge from spreadsheet value to app value
- mix of simple wins and more defensible system assets

## Design and UX Guidance

Future sheet production should follow these principles:

- Design for Google Sheets first.
- Preserve Excel compatibility where practical.
- Include a `Start Here` or `How To Use` tab.
- Use a `Settings` tab for shared variables.
- Use an `Ingredient Master` or equivalent master-data sheet.
- Include a clear summary or dashboard tab.
- Use validation, dropdowns, protected formulas, and input highlighting.
- Make the sheet pleasant and clean, not visually stale.
- Keep the free version genuinely useful.

## Upsell Strategy

The sheet should remain valuable on its own. The app upgrade should appear when spreadsheet limitations become obvious.

Best upsell moments:

- updating ingredient costs across many recipes
- keeping multiple locations aligned
- tracking actual vs theoretical food cost
- maintaining supplier and purchase data
- preserving history and auditability
- collaborating across a team

Recommended ladder:

1. Free Google Sheet
2. Optional web calculator or companion page
3. Free `Foodcosting.app` account
4. Paid app for automation and scale

## What Not To Do

- Do not publish many thin or nearly identical templates.
- Do not make the templates feel like fake lead magnets.
- Do not over-gate value before the user sees the sheet structure or utility.
- Do not rely on generic spreadsheet layouts that ignore kitchen realities like unit conversion, sub-recipes, or yield.

## Suggested Next-Step Work for Agents

- specify the first five Google Sheets products in detail
- define tab structure and formulas for each sheet
- draft landing-page copy and CTA strategy for each asset
- identify naming conventions and SEO angles
- create a reusable template framework across the full sheet family

